Background

The final prototype is (maybe) a failure, I made as much mistakes as possible. In the last ideation, I thought of many interactive ideas like, games,avatars, meters, animation, etc. However, due to technical difficulties, I made a very down-to earth and shabby webpage. The directory links doesn't work, the content crowd together, and they style inconsistent. In other words, the design is very limited and the content is not fruitful.

Research and User Feedback

The website was shown to 4 people, the 4 people are all strangers that can read English in a hospital(failure 1, this is supposed to be a Chinese website). When they saw the website, they laughed awkwardly, as I only have a phone with me, and showingthe the mobil version. The mobile version is just like the pc version. Therefore, the users need to zoom in and in. They tried to interact with the website but the buttons are just too small, they gave up and I pressed the button for them.

For the content, the users kept saying"Too vague! Thats super vague!". In the beginning, I only included the 'card', as the user flip the purple card with the Salvation Army Logo, the text'EveryOne, we help everyone in need'will be displayed. With only that, the user say that is super vague, even a scammer could do better. So, I add an 'about us'page, It talked about 3 main work Salvation Army did. However, its 'not enough' and and the layout and style doesn't look like the rest of the website. "

Wow I won't donate to this website, but good attempt, kid.

Design Ideation

I wishthe webpage could be more interactive. At first, I wanted the webpage to be an-interactive story book that takes the users throught suffering and therefore they should donate. But then, due to programming difficulties, and realization that this might be off topic,I choose the basic format. A navigation bar, a favicon(that won't show up), a place to display photos and addiction pages for information and donation. What I think would imporove the format:

  • The text should have more highlight
  • The format, and seperation of the sections are not clear enough, just bolded words are not enough
  • Try to build the css and html together at the same time. Writing the html first then css can distract my direction

Designs Principles and Concepts

For colours, I used red as the main and only theme, highly related to the Salvation Army. It also contrast with background colour white. All important directions are in red, for example, the nav bar,. As you hover over it, the hovered part would turn red.

There are 2 types of typography in my webpage. The deflaut and Arial. Both are very popular, old and widely-seen fonts. To give the users a sense of securiality and relieability, I avoid to use funky and silly fonts. Moreover, the headlines and impportant words are bolded. For example, the'donate' from the nav bar, emphasizing the importance of the users' suppot, and the main purpose of this webste.'
